ttempted=yes }}\n\n[[Category:Collaboration]]\n[[Category:Bah\u00e1'\u00ed belief and doctrine]]\n[[Category:Mottos]]\n[[Category:Multiculturalism]]\n[[Category:Multiculturalism in Canada]]\n[[Category:Pluralism (philosophy)]]\n", "name_user": "223.189.186.41", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unity_in_diversity"}
{"title_page": "A Simple Heart (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2008 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Simple Heart\n| image          = Un c\u0153ur simple.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Marion Laine]]\n| producer       = B\u00e9atrice Caufman<br>Jean-Michel Rey \n| writer         = [[Gustave Flaubert]]<br>Marion Laine\n| starring       = [[Sandrine Bonnaire]]<br>[[Marina Fo\u00efs]]\n| music          = Cyril Morin \n| cinematography = [[Guillaume Schiffman]]\n| editing        = [[Juliette Welfling]]\n| distributor    = Rezo Films\n| released       = {{Film date|2008|3|26|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         = $3.6 million <ref name=\"Boxoffice\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=10121 |title=Un c\u0153ur simple |accessdate=22 March 2015 |work=jpbox}}</ref>\n| gross          = $889.000 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?id=_fUNCOEURSIMPLE01&country=FR&wk=2008W13&id=_fUNCOEURSIMPLE01&p=.htm|title=Un coeur simple|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''A Simple Heart''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Un c\u0153ur simple'''}}) is a 2008 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Marion Laine]]. It is an adaptation of one of [[Flaubert]]'s ''[[Three Tales (Flaubert)|Three Tales]]''.\n\nThe film was entered into the [[30th Moscow International Film Festival]] where it won the Special Jury Prize.<ref name=\"Moscow2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2008 |title=30th Moscow International Film Festival (2008) |accessdate=2 June 2013 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421050837/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2008 |archivedate=21 April 2013 }}</ref> It won the [[Prix Jacques Pr\u00e9vert du Sc\u00e9nario]] for Best Adaptation in 2009.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Sandrine Bonnaire]] as F\u00e9licit\u00e9\n* [[Marina Fo\u00efs]] as Mathilde Aubain\n* [[Pascal Elb\u00e9]] as Th\u00e9odore\n* [[Patrick Pineau]] as Li\u00e9bard\n* [[Thibault Vin\u00e7on]] as Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric\n* [[No\u00e9mie Lvovsky]] as Nastasie\n* [[Micha\u00ebl Abiteboul]] as Fabu\n* [[Swann Arlaud]] as Paul Aubain\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1064977|A Simple Heart}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simple Heart}}\n[[Category:2008 films]]\n[[Category:2008 drama films]]\n[[Category:Adaptations of works by Gustave Flaubert]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n{{2000s-France-film-stub}}\n{{2000s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2008 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = A Simple Heart\n| image          = Un c\u0153ur simple.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Marion Laine]]\n| producer       = B\u00e9atrice Caufman<br>Jean-Michel Rey \n| writer         = [[Gustave Flaubert]]<br>Marion Laine\n| starring       = [[Sandrine Bonnaire]]<br>[[Marina Fo\u00efs]]\n| music          = Cyril Morin \n| cinematography = [[Guillaume Schiffman]]\n| editing        = [[Juliette Welfling]]\n| distributor    = Rezo Films\n| released       = {{Film date|2008|3|26|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         = $3.6 million <ref name=\"Boxoffice\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=10121 |title=Un c\u0153ur simple |accessdate=22 March 2015 |work=jpbox}}</ref>\n| gross          = $889.000 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?id=_fUNCOEURSIMPLE01&country=FR&wk=2008W13&id=_fUNCOEURSIMPLE01&p=.htm|title=Un coeur simple|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''A Simple Heart''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Un c\u0153ur simple'''}}) is a 2008 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Marion Laine]]. It is an adaptation of one of [[Flaubert]]'s ''[[Three Tales (Flaubert)|Three Tales]]''.\n\nThe film was entered into the [[30th Moscow International Film Festival]] where it won the Special Jury Prize.<ref name=\"Moscow2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2008 |title=30th Moscow International Film Festival (2008) |accessdate=2 June 2013 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421050837/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2008 |archivedate=21 April 2013 }}</ref> It won the [[Prix Jacques Pr\u00e9vert du Sc\u00e9nario]] for Best Adaptation in 2009.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Sandrine Bonnaire]] as F\u00e9licit\u00e9\n* [[Marina Fo\u00efs]] as Mathilde Aubain\n* [[Pascal Elb\u00e9]] as Th\u00e9odore\n* [[Patrick Pineau]] as Li\u00e9bard\n* [[Thibault Vin\u00e7on]] as Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric\n* [[No\u00e9mie Lvovsky]] as Nastasie\n* [[Micha\u00ebl Abiteboul]] as Fabu\n* [[Swann Arlaud]] as Paul Aubain\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1064977|A Simple Heart}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simple Heart}}\n[[Category:2008 films]]\n[[Category:2008 drama films]]\n[[Category:Adaptations of works by Gustave Flaubert]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n{{2000s-France-film-stub}}\n{{2000s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Simple_Heart_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Kilclooney More", "text_new": "{{short description|Townland of County Donegal}}\n{{about|Kilclooney More in County Donegal|the townland in County Galway|Kilclooney}}\n[[File:Kilclooney More Portal Tomb Dg. 70 North-Eastern Chamber SE II 2016 08 30.jpg|thumb|Larger chamber of the eastern portal tomb in Kilclooney More with a capstone that has been described as \u2018birdlike\u2019 or \u2018Concorde-like\u2019 ({{italics correction|''Dg. 70''}})<ref name=\"Lacey\">{{cite encyclopedia |last1=Lacey |first1=Brian |title=Prehistoric Archaeology of Donegal: c. 7000 BC to c. AD 500 |pages=101\u2013106 |encyclopedia=An Historical, Environmental and Cultural Atlas of County Donegal |editor1-last=Mac Laughlin |editor1-first=Jim |editor2-last=Beattie |editor2-first=Se\u00e1n |publisher=Cork University Press |location=Cork |date=2013 |isbn=978-1-85918-494-3 |quote=One of the most striking Neolithic monuments in Donegal is the portal tomb at Kilclooney More, near Ardara. Its 4.2- metre long \u2018birdlike\u2019 capstone is only one of the unusual features of this magnificent structure.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Lacy |first=Brian |title=Donegal |journal=Archaeology Ireland |volume=2 |number=2 |date=1988 |pages=48\u201352 |quote=Among the most impressive is the well-known Kilclooney More tomb with its famous \u2018Concorde-like\u2019 capstone.}}</ref>]]\n'''Kilclooney More''' ({{lang-ga|Cill Chluanadh Mh\u00f3r}},<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.logainm.ie/en/14599 |title=Cill Chluanadh Mh\u00f3r |access-date=2 March 2017}}</ref> meaning church of the pasture)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Flanagan |first1=Deirdre |last2=Flanagan |first2=Laurence |date=1994 |title=Irish Place Names |publisher=Gill & Macmillan |location=Dublin |page=223 |isbn=0-7171-2066-X}}</ref> is a [[townland]] in the northwest of [[Ireland]] in coastal [[County Donegal]]. It is situated halfway between [[Narin, County Donegal|Narin]] and [[Ardara, County Donegal|Ardara]] at the [[R261 road (Ireland)|R261]] on the Loughrea Peninsula.\n\n== Megalithic tombs ==\nKilclooney More belongs to the low-lying land in the west of County Donegal that is prominent for its concentration of [[court tomb|court]] and [[portal tomb]]s. In the [[Neolithic|Neolithic period]] this land was fertile due to a warmer and drier climate, supporting farming communities who crafted ceramics and built tombs which are still described as \u2018magnificent\u2019.<ref name=\"Lacey\" />\n\n=== Portal tomb ''Dg. 68'' ===\n[[File:Kilclooney More 2.jpg|thumb|Western portal tomb of Kilclooney More ({{italics correction|''Dg. 68''}})]]\nThe smaller portal tomb of Kilclooney More is located west of the R261, in a shallow basin north of the Abberachrin River. The eastern portal stone is missing but otherwise the tomb is well preserved. The chamber is comparatively small, measuring 1.45{{nbsp}}m \u00d7 1.2{{nbsp}}m, pointed in SSE direction. It is referred to as {{italics correction|''Dg. 68''}} by Eamon Cody.<ref name=\"lacy-32\">{{cite book |editor-last=Lacy |editor-first=Brian |title=Archaeological Survey of County Donegal |page=32 |publisher=Donegal County Council |location=Lifford |date=1983 |isbn=0-9508407-0-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Cody |first=Eamon |title=Survey of the Megalithic tombs of Ireland, Volume VI, County Donegal |publisher=Stationery Office |location=Dublin |date=2002 |isbn=0-7557-1248-X |pages=93\u201394}}</ref>\n\n=== Court tomb ''Dg. 69'' ===\n[[File:Cromlech on the lands of Kilcluny, Co. Donegal by Rev. Joseph Turner 1799.png|thumb|18th-century drawing of the court tomb of Kilclooney More when the lintel was still in its original place ({{italics correction|''Dg. 69''}})]]\nThe court tomb {{italics correction|''Dg. 69''}} is located north of the portal tomb {{italics correction|''Dg. 68''}} and likewise west of the R261 on flat moorland above the basin on a small hill that provides a commanding outlook in all directions. The gallery of the monument has a length of c. 6{{nbsp}}m and a width of 2.0 to 2.5{{nbsp}}m with three [[orthostat]]s on each side. There are no surviving traces of a segmentation into chambers but de Valera assumes that the tomb consisted of two chambers. A heavy [[lintel]] that still resides on the side stones appears to be displaced and reversed in consideration of an 18th-century drawing that shows the lintel above the front of the gallery. Another lintel appears to be fallen and rests in front.<ref>entry 15 on p. 107: {{cite journal |last=de Valera |first=R. |title=The Court Cairns of Ireland |journal=[[Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy, Section C: <!-- JCW-CleanerBot, please keep it that long --> Archaeology, Celtic Studies, History, Linguistics, Literature]] |volume=60 |date=1959 |pages=9\u2013140 |jstor=25505085}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Lacy |editor-first=Brian |title=Archaeological Survey of County Donegal |page=22 |publisher=Donegal County Council |location=Lifford |date=1983 |isbn=0-9508407-0-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Cody |first=Eamon |title=Survey of the Megalithic tombs of Ireland, Volume VI, County Donegal |publisher=Stationery Office |location=Dublin |date=2002 |isbn=0-7557-1248-X |pages=94\u201396}}</ref>\n\n=== Portal tomb ''Dg. 70'' ===\nEast of the R261 on rough moorland is the larger portal tomb {{italics correction|''Dg. 70''}} with two chambers, 9{{nbsp}}m apart, and a modern field wall in-between. The north-eastern chamber has a roof stone with a length of 4.2{{nbsp}}m which rests on two portal stones, both of 1.8{{nbsp}}m height, and a very small pad-stone which in turn rests on the backstone of 1.3{{nbsp}}m height. The smaller, south-western chamber has portal stones of 1{{nbsp}}m height. The roof stone with a length of 1.9{{nbsp}}m is partly dislodged.<ref name=\"lacy-32\" /><ref name=\"Cody\">{{cite book |last=Cody |first=Eamon |title=Survey of the Megalithic tombs of Ireland, Volume VI, County Donegal |publisher=Stationery Office |location=Dublin |date=2002 |isbn=0-7557-1248-X |pages=96\u201399}}</ref> The [[sill stone]] between the portal stones has a rectangular piece missing, a feature that is shared with the portal tombs of [[Poulnabrone dolmen|Poulnabrone]], Ballybrittas, and Tawnatruffaun. Most of the stones are from grey granite outcrops in close vicinity to the tomb. The backstone in red Ardara granite stands in a stark contrast to the overall grey, it originates possibly from a cliffy [[extrusive rock|extrusion]] 200{{nbsp}}m south of the tomb.<ref>{{cite thesis |type=Ph.D. |last=Mercer |first=Phyllis |title=Ritual aspects of Irish portal tombs |date=2014 |publisher=[[NUI Galway]] |pages=110\u2013111 |hdl=10379/4809 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kilclooney More Portal Tomb Dg. 70 NE 2016 08 30.jpg|thumb|{{italics correction|''Dg. 70''}} with its NE-aligned larger chamber in front and its NNE-aligned smaller chamber in the background]]\nThe poorly-preserved [[cairn]] has a long shape with an NNE alignment that extends over 25{{nbsp}}m. The chambers are in the middle of the cairn with the north-eastern chamber 5{{nbsp}}m inside its northern end. The smaller chamber faces NNE, the larger chamber NE.<ref name=\"Cody\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last=\u00d3 Nuall\u00e1in |first=Se\u00e1n |title=Irish Portal Tombs: Topography, Siting and Distribution |journal=The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland |volume=113 |date=1983 |pages=75\u2013105 |jstor=25508838}} The two portal tombs are listed as numbers 15 and 16 on p. 94. \u00d3 Nuall\u00e1in describes the smaller chamber to be aligned in NNW direction which appears to be wrong. Cody's survey gives an NNE alignment and provides a comparative chart with the alignments of all portal tombs in County Donegal in Fig. 94.</ref> Like almost all coastal portal tombs in Ireland it is oriented away from the sea with the backstone facing the coast.<ref>{{cite thesis |type=Ph.D. |last=Mercer |first=Phyllis |title=Ritual aspects of Irish portal tombs |date=2014 |publisher=[[NUI Galway]] |pages=128,130 |hdl=10379/4809 }}</ref> The combination of a long cairn with a minor chamber as in Kilclooney More and Ballyrennan in [[County Tyrone]] is seen by \u00d3 Nuall\u00e1in as an indication that portal tombs evolved from court tombs.<ref>{{cite journal |last=\u00d3 Nuall\u00e1in |first=Se\u00e1n |title=The Megalithic Tombs of Ireland: Neolithic Tombs and their Art |journal=Expedition |volume=21 |number=3 |date=1979 |pages=6\u201315 |url=https://www.penn.museum/documents/publications/expedition/PDFs/21-3/Nuallain.pdf}}</ref>\n\nMultiple sherds of Neolithic pottery, all belonging to one quartz-tempered vessel with fine textures, were found in the larger chamber and are now in the possession of the [[National Museum of Ireland]].<ref>Items 64\u201366 at p. 18 in: {{cite journal |last1=Lucas |first1=A. T. |last2=Raftery |first2=Joseph |author3-link=Ellen Prendergast |first3=Ellen |last3=Prendergast |last4=\u00d3 R\u00edord\u00e1in |first4=Breand\u00e1n |last5=Rynne |first5=Etienne |title=National Museum of Ireland Archaeological Acquisitions in the Year 1958 |journal=The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland |volume=90 |number=1 |date=1960 |pages=1\u201340 |jstor=25509378}}</ref><ref>Item 9 at p. 138 in: {{cite journal |last=Herity |first=Michael |title=The Finds from the Irish Portal Dolmens |journal=The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland |volume=94 |number=2 |date=1964 |pages=123\u2013144 |jstor=25509566}}</ref><ref>p. 319 in: {{cite journal |last=Herity |first=Michael |title=Irish Decorated Neolithic Pottery |journal=[[Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy, Section C:<!-- JCW-CleanerBot, please keep it that long --> Archaeology, Celtic Studies, History, Linguistics, Literature]] |volume=82C |date=1982 |pages=247\u2013404 |jstor=25506090}}</ref> Dating of Irish portal tombs is difficult as no radiocarbon dates are available. However, the sherds are assumed to belong to the [[Grimston-Lyles Hill ware|''Lyles Hill'']] series of pottery which can be approximately dated as this kind of pottery has been found close to fireplaces at other sites. In consideration of this context, Arthur ApSimon estimates that portal tombs like those of Kilclooney More belong to a period from 5000 to 4800 [[Before Present|BP]], i.e. from ca. 3780 to ca. 3550 [[Anno Domini|BC]], which falls into the early Neolithic period.<ref>{{cite journal |last=ApSimon |first=Arthur |title=Chronological Contexts for Irish Megalithic Tombs |journal=The Journal of Irish Archaeology |volume=3 |date=1985 |pages=5\u201315 |jstor=30001633}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.townlands.ie/donegal/boylagh/inishkeel/dawros/kilclooney-more/ entry at townlands.ie]\n\n{{Coord|54.817718|-8.4331537|display=title}}<!-- coordinates of the portal tomb Dg. 70 which is the most prominent feature of this townland -->\n\n{{County Donegal}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Donegal]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in County Donegal]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Townland of County Donegal}}\n{{about|Kilclooney More in County Donegal|the townland in County Galway|Kilclooney}}\n[[File:Kilclooney More Portal Tomb Dg. 70 North-Eastern Chamber SE II 2016 08 30.jpg|thumb|Larger chamber of the eastern portal tomb in Kilclooney More with a capstone that has been described as \u2018birdlike\u2019 or \u2018Concorde-like\u2019 ({{italics correction|''Dg. 70''}})<ref name=\"Lacey\">{{cite encyclopedia |last1=Lacey |first1=Brian |title=Prehistoric Archaeology of Donegal: c. 7000 BC to c. AD 500 |pages=101\u2013106 |encyclopedia=An Historical, Environmental and Cultural Atlas of County Donegal |editor1-last=Mac Laughlin |editor1-first=Jim |editor2-last=Beattie |editor2-first=Se\u00e1n |publisher=Cork University Press |location=Cork |date=2013 |isbn=978-1-85918-494-3 |quote=One of the most striking Neolithic monuments in Donegal is the portal tomb at Kilclooney More, near Ardara. Its 4.2- metre long \u2018birdlike\u2019 capstone is only one of the unusual features of this magnificent structure.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Lacy |first=Brian |title=Donegal |journal=Archaeology Ireland |volume=2 |number=2 |date=1988 |pages=48\u201352 |quote=Among the most impressive is the well-known Kilclooney More tomb with its famous \u2018Concorde-like\u2019 capstone.}}</ref>]]\n'''Kilclooney More''' ({{lang-ga|Cill Chluanadh Mh\u00f3r}},<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.logainm.ie/en/14599 |title=Cill Chluanadh Mh\u00f3r |access-date=2 March 2017}}</ref> meaning church of the pasture)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Flanagan |first1=Deirdre |last2=Flanagan |first2=Laurence |date=1994 |title=Irish Place Names |publisher=Gill & Macmillan |location=Dublin |page=223 |isbn=0-7171-2066-X}}</ref> is a [[townland]] in the northwest of [[Ireland]] in coastal [[County Donegal]]. It is situated halfway between [[Narin, County Donegal|Narin]] and [[Ardara, County Donegal|Ardara]] at the [[R261 road (Ireland)|R261]] on the Loughrea Peninsula.\n\n== Megalithic tombs ==\nKilclooney More belongs to the low-lying land in the west of County Donegal that is prominent for its concentration of [[court tomb|court]] and [[portal tomb]]s. In the [[Neolithic|Neolithic period]] this land was fertile due to a warmer and drier climate, supporting farming communities who crafted ceramics and built tombs which are still described as \u2018magnificent\u2019.<ref name=\"Lacey\" />\n\n=== Portal tomb ''Dg. 68'' ===\n[[File:Kilclooney More 2.jpg|thumb|Western portal tomb of Kilclooney More ({{italics correction|''Dg. 68''}})]]\nThe smaller portal tomb of Kilclooney More is located west of the R261, in a shallow basin north of the Abberachrin River. The eastern portal stone is missing but otherwise the tomb is well preserved. The chamber is comparatively small, measuring 1.45{{nbsp}}m \u00d7 1.2{{nbsp}}m, pointed in SSE direction. It is referred to as {{italics correction|''Dg. 68''}} by Eamon Cody.<ref name=\"lacy-32\">{{cite book |editor-last=Lacy |editor-first=Brian |title=Archaeological Survey of County Donegal |page=32 |publisher=Donegal County Council |location=Lifford |date=1983 |isbn=0-9508407-0-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Cody |first=Eamon |title=Survey of the Megalithic tombs of Ireland, Volume VI, County Donegal |publisher=Stationery Office |location=Dublin |date=2002 |isbn=0-7557-1248-X |pages=93\u201394}}</ref>\n\n=== Court tomb ''Dg. 69'' ===\n[[File:Cromlech on the lands of Kilcluny, Co. Donegal by Rev. Joseph Turner 1799.png|thumb|18th-century drawing of the court tomb of Kilclooney More when the lintel was still in its original place ({{italics correction|''Dg. 69''}})]]\nThe court tomb {{italics correction|''Dg. 69''}} is located north of the portal tomb {{italics correction|''Dg. 68''}} and likewise west of the R261 on flat moorland above the basin on a small hill that provides a commanding outlook in all directions. The gallery of the monument has a length of c. 6{{nbsp}}m and a width of 2.0 to 2.5{{nbsp}}m with three [[orthostat]]s on each side. There are no surviving traces of a segmentation into chambers but de Valera assumes that the tomb consisted of two chambers. A heavy [[lintel]] that still resides on the side stones appears to be displaced and reversed in consideration of an 18th-century drawing that shows the lintel above the front of the gallery. Another lintel appears to be fallen and rests in front.<ref>entry 15 on p. 107: {{cite journal |last=de Valera |first=R. |title=The Court Cairns of Ireland |journal=[[Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy, Section C: <!-- JCW-CleanerBot, please keep it that long --> Archaeology, Celtic Studies, History, Linguistics, Literature]] |volume=60 |date=1959 |pages=9\u2013140 |jstor=25505085}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Lacy |editor-first=Brian |title=Archaeological Survey of County Donegal |page=22 |publisher=Donegal County Council |location=Lifford |date=1983 |isbn=0-9508407-0-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Cody |first=Eamon |title=Survey of the Megalithic tombs of Ireland, Volume VI, County Donegal |publisher=Stationery Office |location=Dublin |date=2002 |isbn=0-7557-1248-X |pages=94\u201396}}</ref>\n\n=== Portal tomb ''Dg. 70'' ===\nEast of the R261 on rough moorland is the larger portal tomb {{italics correction|''Dg. 70''}} with two chambers, 9{{nbsp}}m apart, and a modern field wall in-between. The north-eastern chamber has a roof stone with a length of 4.2{{nbsp}}m which rests on two portal stones, both of 1.8{{nbsp}}m height, and a very small pad-stone which in turn rests on the backstone of 1.3{{nbsp}}m height. The smaller, south-western chamber has portal stones of 1{{nbsp}}m height. The roof stone with a length of 1.9{{nbsp}}m is partly dislodged.<ref name=\"lacy-32\" /><ref name=\"Cody\">{{cite book |last=Cody |first=Eamon |title=Survey of the Megalithic tombs of Ireland, Volume VI, County Donegal |publisher=Stationery Office |location=Dublin |date=2002 |isbn=0-7557-1248-X |pages=96\u201399}}</ref> The [[sill stone]] between the portal stones has a rectangular piece missing, a feature that is shared with the portal tombs of [[Poulnabrone dolmen|Poulnabrone]], Ballybrittas, and Tawnatruffaun. Most of the stones are from grey granite outcrops in close vicinity to the tomb. The backstone in red Ardara granite stands in a stark contrast to the overall grey, it originates possibly from a cliffy [[extrusive rock|extrusion]] 200{{nbsp}}m south of the tomb.<ref>{{cite thesis |type=Ph.D. |last=Mercer |first=Phyllis |title=Ritual aspects of Irish portal tombs |date=2014 |publisher=[[NUI Galway]] |pages=110\u2013111 |hdl=10379/4809 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kilclooney More Portal Tomb Dg. 70 NE 2016 08 30.jpg|thumb|{{italics correction|''Dg. 70''}} with its NE-aligned larger chamber in front and its NNE-aligned smaller chamber in the background]]\nThe poorly-preserved [[cairn]] has a long shape with an NNE alignment that extends over 25{{nbsp}}m. The chambers are in the middle of the cairn with the north-eastern chamber 5{{nbsp}}m inside its northern end. The smaller chamber faces NNE, the larger chamber NE.<ref name=\"Cody\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last=\u00d3 Nuall\u00e1in |first=Se\u00e1n |title=Irish Portal Tombs: Topography, Siting and Distribution |journal=The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland |volume=113 |date=1983 |pages=75\u2013105 |jstor=25508838}} The two portal tombs are listed as numbers 15 and 16 on p. 94. \u00d3 Nuall\u00e1in describes the smaller chamber to be aligned in NNW direction which appears to be wrong. Cody's survey gives an NNE alignment and provides a comparative chart with the alignments of all portal tombs in County Donegal in Fig. 94.</ref> Like almost all coastal portal tombs in Ireland it is oriented away from the sea with the backstone facing the coast.<ref>{{cite thesis |type=Ph.D. |last=Mercer |first=Phyllis |title=Ritual aspects of Irish portal tombs |date=2014 |publisher=[[NUI Galway]] |pages=128,130 |hdl=10379/4809 }}</ref> The combination of a long cairn with a minor chamber as in Kilclooney More and Ballyrennan in [[County Tyrone]] is seen by \u00d3 Nuall\u00e1in as an indication that portal tombs evolved from court tombs.<ref>{{cite journal |last=\u00d3 Nuall\u00e1in |first=Se\u00e1n |title=The Megalithic Tombs of Ireland: Neolithic Tombs and their Art |journal=Expedition |volume=21 |number=3 |date=1979 |pages=6\u201315 |url=https://www.penn.museum/documents/publications/expedition/PDFs/21-3/Nuallain.pdf}}</ref>\n\nMultiple sherds of Neolithic pottery, all belonging to one quartz-tempered vessel with fine textures, were found in the larger chamber and are now in the possession of the [[National Museum of Ireland]].<ref>Items 64\u201366 at p. 18 in: {{cite journal |last1=Lucas |first1=A. T. |last2=Raftery |first2=Joseph |author3-link=Ellen Prendergast |last3=Ellen Prendergast |last4=\u00d3 R\u00edord\u00e1in |first4=Breand\u00e1n |last5=Rynne |first5=Etienne |title=National Museum of Ireland Archaeological Acquisitions in the Year 1958 |journal=The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland |volume=90 |number=1 |date=1960 |pages=1\u201340 |jstor=25509378}}</ref><ref>Item 9 at p. 138 in: {{cite journal |last=Herity |first=Michael |title=The Finds from the Irish Portal Dolmens |journal=The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland |volume=94 |number=2 |date=1964 |pages=123\u2013144 |jstor=25509566}}</ref><ref>p. 319 in: {{cite journal |last=Herity |first=Michael |title=Irish Decorated Neolithic Pottery |journal=[[Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy, Section C:<!-- JCW-CleanerBot, please keep it that long --> Archaeology, Celtic Studies, History, Linguistics, Literature]] |volume=82C |date=1982 |pages=247\u2013404 |jstor=25506090}}</ref> Dating of Irish portal tombs is difficult as no radiocarbon dates are available. However, the sherds are assumed to belong to the [[Grimston-Lyles Hill ware|''Lyles Hill'']] series of pottery which can be approximately dated as this kind of pottery has been found close to fireplaces at other sites. In consideration of this context, Arthur ApSimon estimates that portal tombs like those of Kilclooney More belong to a period from 5000 to 4800 [[Before Present|BP]], i.e. from ca. 3780 to ca. 3550 [[Anno Domini|BC]], which falls into the early Neolithic period.<ref>{{cite journal |last=ApSimon |first=Arthur |title=Chronological Contexts for Irish Megalithic Tombs |journal=The Journal of Irish Archaeology |volume=3 |date=1985 |pages=5\u201315 |jstor=30001633}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.townlands.ie/donegal/boylagh/inishkeel/dawros/kilclooney-more/ entry at townlands.ie]\n\n{{Coord|54.817718|-8.4331537|display=title}}<!-- coordinates of the portal tomb Dg. 70 which is the most prominent feature of this townland -->\n\n{{County Donegal}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Donegal]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in County Donegal]]\n", "name_user": "AFBorchert", "label": "safe", "comment": "reference fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilclooney_More"}
{"title_page": "The Ages of Lulu", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Ages of Lulu\n| image          = Las edades de lulu.jpg\n| image size     = 250px\n| border         =\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Spanish original theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Bigas Luna]]\n| producer       = [[Andr\u00e9s Vicente G\u00f3mez]]\n| screenplay     = Bigas Luna\n| based on       = {{Based on|Novel ''The Ages of Lulu''|[[Almudena Grandes]]}}\n| starring       = [[Francesca Neri]]<br>[[Mar\u00eda Barranco]]<br>[[Javier Bardem]]<br>[[Fernando Guill\u00e9n Cuervo]]<br>[[Rosana Pastor]]<br>[[Pilar Bardem]]\n| music          = Carlos Segarra\n| cinematography = Fernando Arribas\n| editing        = Pablo Gonz\u00e1lez del Amo\n| studio         = Iberoamericana Films Internacional\nApricot\n| distributor    = Umbrella Entertainment\n| released       = {{Film date|1990| | |Spain}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = Spain\n| language       = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n'''''The Ages of Lulu''''' ({{lang-es|'''Las edades de Lul\u00fa'''}}) is a 1990 [[Cinema of Spain|Spanish]] [[erotic film|erotic]] [[drama film]] written and directed by [[Bigas Luna]] and starring [[Francesca Neri]], \u00d3scar Ladoire, [[Mar\u00eda Barranco]] and [[Javier Bardem]]. It is based on the homonymous novel by [[Almudena Grandes]]. The film is about the title character's life and sexual awakening in [[Madrid]], which leads to her involvement in increasingly dangerous sexual experimentation.\n\n== Plot summary ==\nThe fifteen-year-old Lul\u00fa is seduced by Pablo, her brother Marcelo's best friend, who then leaves to work in the United States.  Lul\u00fa is sustained for years by the belief that Pablo will come back into her life.  When he returns he proposes to her and they are married.  Pablo and Lul\u00fa have a passionate relationship, developing a taste for sexual games.  \n\nOn one nocturnal expedition they join up with a transgender prostitute called Ely who becomes their friend.  The couple have a daughter, Ines.  Pablo convinces Lul\u00fa to participate blindfolded in a threesome; when Lul\u00fa discovers that the third person was Marcelo, her brother, she leaves Pablo in disgust, taking their daughter with her.  However, her own desire to play increasingly dangerous sex games now comes to consume her. \n\nAfter becoming aroused watching a [[gay porn]] movie, she seeks out [[gay]] men and pays them to join in orgies, or watch them having sex.  Unable to pay enough to satisfy her desires, she meets a pimp called Remy who runs a secret [[sadomasochism|S&M]] club.  Ely tries to warn Lul\u00fa that Remy is dangerous, but Lul\u00fa ignores her, so Ely goes to warn Pablo.  Remy tells Lul\u00fa to go to a club, where she is tied up by Jimmy, a gay man she had previously paid for sex. \n\nShe is forced to endure violent sex while gagged and bound.  Ely tells Pablo that Lul\u00fa is in danger.  She goes to the club to rescue her, but is attacked by Jimmy and killed when her head hits a metal bar.  Pablo calls the police, who arrest Jimmy and the others.  Lul\u00fa and Pablo are reunited.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Francesca Neri]] as Lul\u00fa\n* \u00d3scar Ladoire as Pablo\n* [[Mar\u00eda Barranco]] as Ely\n* [[Javier Bardem]] as Jimmy\n* [[Fernando Guill\u00e9n Cuervo]] as Marcelo\n* [[Rosana Pastor]] as Chelo\n* Juan Graell as Remy\n* Rodrigo Valverde as Pablito\n* [[Pilar Bardem]] as Encarna\n* [[Marta May]] as Lul\u00fa's mother\n* Gloria Rodriquez as Cristina\n* \u00c1ngel Jov\u00e8 as Alicantino\n* Ainara P\u00e9rez as Lul\u00fa as a child\n* Juan Sala as Lul\u00fa's father\n* Pepa Serrano as Flamenca\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nThe film is an adaptation of the international best-selling novel with the same name written by [[Almudena Grandes]]. [[\u00c1ngela Molina]], who was originally cast in the lead role, withdrew when she learned how explicit the sex scenes were to be.\n\n[[Javier Bardem]] has a small, uncredited role as a corrupt [[gay]] man, one of his first roles on screen.\n\nNeri is dubbed into [[Spanish language|Spanish]] by another actress.\n\n== Cuts in UK version ==\nThe film was cut in the [[UK]] by two minutes and 55 seconds by the [[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC]]. These cuts include an [[Sadomasochism|S&M]] orgy at a gay club being shortened, a man sexually touching Lulu and a sex scene; these scenes were restored for the 2002 DVD release. In addition to these cuts an opening scene in which Lulu is [[Baptism|baptised]] as a baby was cut as the child's genitalia is exposed to camera; this shot is considered to be in breach of the [[Protection of Children Act 1978]]. The 2002 UK DVD required 1:15 cuts for baptism scene; a new title sequence was used instead.\n\n== Reception ==\n<!--  Note: Zero critics listed at [[Rotten Tomatoes]] user votes not allowed.<ref>{{cite web | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | url   = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ages-of-lulu/ | title = AGES OF LULU (1990) | access-date = 16 September 2010 }}</ref> -->\n\n''The Ages of Lulu'' was listed on Film4's 50 Sexiest Film Moments.<ref>http://www.film4.com/galleries/50-sexiest-film-moments/the-ages-of-lulu Retrieved on 16 September 2010</ref>\n\n[[Mar\u00eda Barranco]] won the [[Goya Award]] as Best Supporting Actress for her role as a [[transsexual]] [[prostitute]].\n\n== Home Media ==\n''The Ages of Lulu'' was released on [[DVD]] by Umbrella Entertainment in December 2011. The DVD is compatible with region code 4.<ref name=\"Umbrella Entertainment\">{{cite web|title=Umbrella Entertainment|url=http://www.umbrellaent.com.au/p-3110-ages-of-lulu-the.aspx|accessdate=20 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004232537/http://www.umbrellaent.com.au/p-3110-ages-of-lulu-the.aspx|archivedate=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links 